            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kaiya Sharma\u2019s world was always a blend. Born in Fremont to an Indian-immigrant father, an engineer who measured life in data points, and a third-generation Japanese-American mother, a graphic designer who saw life in color palettes, Kaiya grew up navigating intersections. This upbringing instilled in her a unique ability to observe, empathize, and synthesize\u2014skills she wouldn't fully appreciate until later.\n\nHer educational journey began conventionally at a large state university, majoring in Communications. However, after two years adrift in abstract theory, she felt a profound disconnect. The turning point came during a listless summer working as a barista. A long conversation with her mother about the logic behind visual communication sparked an interest in digital design. Kaiya discovered the world of User Experience (UX), a perfect marriage of her father\u2019s analytical pragmatism and her mother\u2019s creative intuition. She dropped out of college, invested her savings in an intensive San Francisco UX Design Bootcamp, and never looked back.\n\nNow, at 25, Kaiya is an Associate Product Designer at a mid-size tech firm in SoMa that creates data visualization tools for scientific professionals. Her days are spent translating complex user needs into elegant, intuitive interfaces. Her 3.5-mile MUNI bus ride from her Inner Richmond apartment is a cherished ritual, a time to listen to design podcasts while the city rumbles to life.\n\nShe shares a classic Edwardian flat with two roommates, a UCSF nurse and a grad student. Life is a careful balance on her $98,000 salary\u2014enough for comfort, but requiring mindful budgeting. Her social life revolves around a tight-knit group of friends from her bootcamp, exploring new restaurants on Clement Street or going for long runs through Golden Gate Park. San Francisco, with its vibrant, overlapping cultures, feels like the first place she\u2019s truly belonged. Kaiya dreams of one day leading a design team for a company with a strong social mission, hoping to design products that don\u2019t just function beautifully, but genuinely improve people\u2019s lives."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe recalls the oppressive Fremont summer heat when she was 20, feeling adrift. Her mother was sketching at the kitchen table, and Kaiya finally asked her, \"How do you *know* it works?\" Her mom paused, then walked her through the grid system, the color theory, the invisible logic holding the art together. It wasn't just feeling; it was a system. In that explanation, Kaiya felt the two halves of her world\u2014her father's data and her mother's design\u2014click into place. It was the moment a map appeared for a future she could finally navigate.\n\n2.\nThe bootcamp classroom was dark except for the glow of their screens. It was 1 a.m., and her team was stuck on a convoluted user flow. Frustrated, Kaiya stood up and went to the whiteboard. She stopped thinking about the interface and started drawing the user\u2019s emotions\u2014confusion, discovery, relief. The solution wasn't a series of buttons, but a pathway. Her instructor saw the diagram and simply nodded. \"That's it.\" The pride she felt wasn't just academic; it was the visceral, bone-deep certainty that she had made the right choice.\n\n3.\nIt was her first real San Francisco moment. She was 23, running with her friends through Golden Gate Park on a typically foggy morning. The damp air smelled of eucalyptus and earth. Afterwards, shivering and laughing, they crammed into a tiny Clement Street restaurant for dim sum. The clatter of carts, the warmth of the tea, the shared joy with friends who *got it*\u2014it was the first time the city didn't feel like a place she was just visiting. It felt like a place that was holding her.\n\n4.\nShe was terrified presenting her first big project at work. The lead scientist, a woman she deeply respected, was famously skeptical. Kaiya explained the user research, the wireframes, the new dashboard layout. The scientist squinted at the screen, silent for a long minute. \"This simplifies a three-hour process into ten minutes,\" she said finally, looking directly at Kaiya. \"This is good work.\" The praise wasn't just for a good design; it was validation that her work could genuinely help people. It planted the seed for what she wanted to do next.\n\n5.\nThe 38R MUNI bus is her quiet sanctuary. A few months ago, while listening to a podcast on accessible design, she looked up as the bus groaned over a hill. The morning fog had parted, revealing the downtown skyline bathed in an impossible golden light. The podcast dialogue, the rumble of the bus, the sudden, breathtaking view\u2014it was a perfect composition. In that fleeting moment, she felt an overwhelming sense of gratitude and purpose, sketching an idea in her notebook as her city woke up around her."
